06082nam a22009375i 9781501749193DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019040743  a97815017491937 a10.1515/97815017491932doi  a(DE-B1597)537535  a(OCoLC)1198930283  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPR478.M6bL49 2020 4aPR478.M6bL49 2021 7aPHO0100002bisacsh04a820.9/00922231 aLewis, Cara L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDynamic Form :bHow Intermediality Made Modernism /cCara L. Lewis. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (330 p.) :b28 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Reformulating Modernism -- t1. Plastic Form: Henry James’s Sculptural Aesthetics and Reading in the Round -- t2. Mortal Form: Still Life and Virginia Woolf ’s Other Elegiac Shapes -- t3. Protean Form: Erotic Abstraction and Ardent Futurity in the Poetry of Mina Loy -- t4. Bad Formalism: Evelyn Waugh’s Film Fictions and the Work of Art in the Age of Cinemechanics -- t5. Surface Forms: Photography and Gertrude Stein’s Contact History of Modernism -- tEpilogue: The Consolations of Form -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDynamic Form traces how intermedial experiments shape modernist texts from 1900 to 1950. Considering literature alongside painting, sculpture, photography, and film, Cara Lewis examines how these arts inflect narrative movement, contribute to plot events, and configure poetry and memoir. As forms and formal theories cross from one artistic realm to another and back again, modernism shows its obsession with form—and even at times becomes a formalism itself—but as Lewis writes, that form is far more dynamic than we have given it credit for. Form fulfills such various functions that we cannot characterize it as a mere container for content or matter, nor can we consign it to ignominy opposite historicism or political commitment.As a structure or scheme that enables action, form in modernism can be plastic, protean, or even fragile, and works by Henry James, Virginia Woolf, Mina Loy, Evelyn Waugh, and Gertrude Stein demonstrate the range of form's operations. Revising three major formal paradigms—spatial form, pure form, and formlessness—and recasting the history of modernist form, this book proposes an understanding of form as a verbal category, as a kind of doing. Dynamic Form thus opens new possibilities for conversation between modernist studies and formalist studies and simultaneously promotes a capacious rethinking of the convergence between literary modernism and creative work in other media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAmerian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArt and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFormalism (Art)xHistory. 0aFormalism (Literary analysis)xHistory. 0aLiterary formxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Art)zGreat Britain. 0aModernism (Art)zUnited States. 0aModernism (Literature)zGreat Britain. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 4aArt History. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhotography. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh  amodernism, visual arts, media, literary form, art in literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z9783110690460